{"title_page": "James T. Lane", "text_new": "\n\n[[File:James-T-Lane.jpg]]\n\n\n'''James T. Lane''' (born December 25, 1977) is an [[United States|American]] actor and dancer. He made his Broadway debut with the 2006 revival of ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', playing Richie Walters.<ref>http://www.achorusline.com/achorusline_cast_james.php</ref> After that, Lane joined the cast of ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago: The Musical]]'',<ref>[http://chicagothemusical.com/cast_ny.php?start=12&id_tb_cast=456 Broadway cast], Chicago: The Musical.</ref> playing the role of Aaron and Amos. Other credits include an episode on ''[[One Life to Live]]'' as a [[James Brown]] impersonator.<ref name=\"imdb.com\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3394045/ James T. Lane] at IMDb.</ref> Lane was last been seen on Broadway in ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', playing the roles of Ozie Powell and Ruby Bates.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scottsboromusical.com/cast.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027091727/http://scottsboromusical.com/cast.html |archive-date=2010-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2013, Lane reprised his ''A Chorus Line'' role in The West End.\n\n==Early life==\nJames T. Lane was born and raised in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"imdb.com\"/> He attended the Meredith School from kindergarten until 8th grade. During his high school years Lane attended the [[Girard Academic Music Program]]. During his teen years, he attended the Ensemble Theatre Community School in [[Eagles Mere, Pennsylvania]]. After high school, Lane studied musical theatre at [[Carnegie-Mellon]] and [[Penn State]].\n\n==Broadway==\n* ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', as Richie Walters, 2006\u201308\n* ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago: The Musical]]'', as Aaron/Amos Hart, 2008\u201310; 2015\n* ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', as Ozie Powell/Ruby Bates, 2010\n* ''[[King Kong (2013 musical)|King Kong]]'', as Ensemble, 2018\n* ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'', as Paul, 2019\n\n==West End==\n* ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', as Richie Walters, 2013\n* ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', as Ozie Powell/Ruby Bates, 2014\u201315\n\n==Other theatre credits==\n* ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'', as Paul - Hartford Stage/Old Globe, 2015\n* ''[[Jersey Boys]]'', as Barry Belson - USA tour, 2012\n* ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', as Ozie Powell/Ruby Bates \u2013 San Diego, San Francisco, 2012\n* ''[[Dreamgirls]]'' \u2013 [[Prince Music Theatre]], 2005<ref>http://broadwayworld.com/people/?personid=12758</ref>\n* ''[[Cole Porter's The Pirate]]'' \u2013 [[Prince Music Theatre]], 2006 <ref>Prince Theater playbill, May 2006</ref>\n* ''[[Finian's Rainbow]]'' - [[Walnut Street Theatre]]\n* ''[[Fame (musical)|Fame]]'' as Tyrone \n* ''[[Cinderella (musical)|Cinderella]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb name|id=3394045|name=James T. Lane}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lane, James T.}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American dancers]]\n[[Category:American male dancers]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n[File:James-T-Lane.jpg|thumb]]\n| imagesize =\n| caption                  =\n| name                    = James T. Lane\n| birth_name               = James Tyrone Lane\n| birth_date               = {{birth date and age|1977|12|25}}\n| birth_place              = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date               =\n| death_place              =\n| restingplace            =\n| restingplacecoordinates =\n| othername               =\n| occupation              = [[Actor]], [[dance]]r\n| yearsactive             =\n| spouse                  =\n| partner                 =\n| children                =\n| parents                 =\n| influences              =\n| influenced              =\n| website                 =\n}}\n\n'''James T. Lane''' (born December 25, 1977) is an [[United States|American]] actor and dancer. He made his Broadway debut with the 2006 revival of ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', playing Richie Walters.<ref>http://www.achorusline.com/achorusline_cast_james.php</ref> After that, Lane joined the cast of ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago: The Musical]]'',<ref>[http://chicagothemusical.com/cast_ny.php?start=12&id_tb_cast=456 Broadway cast], Chicago: The Musical.</ref> playing the role of Aaron and Amos. Other credits include an episode on ''[[One Life to Live]]'' as a [[James Brown]] impersonator.<ref name=\"imdb.com\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3394045/ James T. Lane] at IMDb.</ref> Lane was last been seen on Broadway in ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', playing the roles of Ozie Powell and Ruby Bates.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scottsboromusical.com/cast.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101027091727/http://scottsboromusical.com/cast.html |archive-date=2010-10-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2013, Lane reprised his ''A Chorus Line'' role in The West End.\n\n==Early life==\nJames T. Lane was born and raised in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"imdb.com\"/> He attended the Meredith School from kindergarten until 8th grade. During his high school years Lane attended the [[Girard Academic Music Program]]. During his teen years, he attended the Ensemble Theatre Community School in [[Eagles Mere, Pennsylvania]]. After high school, Lane studied musical theatre at [[Carnegie-Mellon]] and [[Penn State]].\n\n==Broadway==\n* ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', as Richie Walters, 2006\u201308\n* ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago: The Musical]]'', as Aaron/Amos Hart, 2008\u201310; 2015\n* ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', as Ozie Powell/Ruby Bates, 2010\n* ''[[King Kong (2013 musical)|King Kong]]'', as Ensemble, 2018\n* ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'', as Paul, 2019\n\n==West End==\n* ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', as Richie Walters, 2013\n* ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', as Ozie Powell/Ruby Bates, 2014\u201315\n\n==Other theatre credits==\n* ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'', as Paul - Hartford Stage/Old Globe, 2015\n* ''[[Jersey Boys]]'', as Barry Belson - USA tour, 2012\n* ''[[The Scottsboro Boys (musical)|The Scottsboro Boys]]'', as Ozie Powell/Ruby Bates \u2013 San Diego, San Francisco, 2012\n* ''[[Dreamgirls]]'' \u2013 [[Prince Music Theatre]], 2005<ref>http://broadwayworld.com/people/?personid=12758</ref>\n* ''[[Cole Porter's The Pirate]]'' \u2013 [[Prince Music Theatre]], 2006 <ref>Prince Theater playbill, May 2006</ref>\n* ''[[Finian's Rainbow]]'' - [[Walnut Street Theatre]]\n* ''[[Fame (musical)|Fame]]'' as Tyrone \n* ''[[Cinderella (musical)|Cinderella]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb name|id=3394045|name=James T. Lane}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lane, James T.}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American dancers]]\n[[Category:American male dancers]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "11aysc", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_T._Lane"}
{"title_page": "Ant\u00f3nio Garrido (referee)", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese football referee}}\n{{Portuguese name|Silva|Garrido}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name  = Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 da Silva Garrido\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1932|12|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Vieira de Leiria, [[Marinha Grande]], Portugal\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2014|9|10|1932|12|3|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Portuguese\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = [[Accountant]]\n| known_for   = [[Referee (association football)|Football referee]] <small>(1964\u20131982)</small>\n}}\n\n'''Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 da Silva Garrido''' <small>[[Order of Prince Henry|OIH]]</small> (3 December 1932 \u2013 10 September 2014) was a Portuguese [[association football|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in Vieira de Leiria, [[Marinha Grande]], Garrido was the first Portuguese referee to officiate a [[1980 European Cup Final|European Cup final]] in 1980. He refereed three matches in the [[FIFA World Cup]], two in the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]] and one in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]] \u2013 the 3rd place play-off match. He also refereed one match in the [[UEFA Euro 1980]] and the first leg of [[1977 European Super Cup]].<ref name=\"publico\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publico.pt/desporto/noticia/antonio-garrido-o-homem-que-detestava-arbitros-mas-tornouse-um-deles-1669273 |title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido, o homem que detestava \u00e1rbitros mas que se tornou um deles |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido, the man who hated referees but that became one of them |author=Tiago Pimentel |date=10 September 2014 |website= |publisher=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]] |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 1983, Garrido received the title of Officer of the [[Order of Prince Henry]]. Although he was an [[accountant]] by profession, he continued involved in football after his forced retirement as a referee in 1982 due to age limit.<ref name=\"expresso\">{{cite web|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/morreu-o-arbitro-que-se-dizia-do-sporting-mas-colaborou-com-o-fc-porto=f888974|title=Morreu o \u00e1rbitro que se dizia do Sporting mas colaborou com o FC Porto|date=10 September 2014|website=|publisher=[[Expresso (Portuguese newspaper)|Expresso]]|language=Portuguese|trans-title=The referee who said being a Sporting fan but who collaborated with FC Porto|last1=Paulo|first1=Isabel|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> He then had several positions, becoming member of the [[Portuguese Football Federation|FPF]]'s Refereeing Board (for 4 years), [[FIFA]] referee instructor, [[UEFA]] observer, and referees commissioner in World Cups (for 20 years).<ref name=\"publico\"/><ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido: \"Marquei penalties quase sem ter visto\" |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido: \"I whistled penalties almost without seeing them\" |url=http://www.jornaldeleiria.pt/portal/index.php?id=7538 |accessdate=10 September 2014 |work=Jornal de Leiria |date=26 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910111809/http://www.jornaldeleiria.pt/portal/index.php?id=7538 |archivedate=10 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Garrido was heard as a witness in Portuguese corruption scandal [[Apito Dourado]] (Golden Whistle) for being tapped talking to Pinto de Sousa (Chairman of the FPF's Refereeing Board) and [[Valentim Loureiro]] (Chairman of the [[Portuguese League for Professional Football]]).<ref name=\"publico\"/><ref name=\"marca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/05/04/futbol/europa_league/1304504345.html|title=Directivos del Oporto cenaron con el \u00e1rbitro tras el partido contra el Villarreal|date=4 May 2011|website=[[Marca.com]]|language=Spanish|trans-title=FC Porto members dined with the referee after the match against Villarreal|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===1978 World Cup===\nGarrido officiated the match between the hosts [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Scott Murray and Paul Doyle|date=2 July 2010|title=The Joy of Six: World Cup Refereeing Controversies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/jul/02/joy-six-world-cup-refereeing-controversies|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== UEFA Euro 1980 ===\nGarrido also officiated the match between Italy and Belgium at [[UEFA Euro 1980]].\n\n==Personal life and death==\nIn 2012, Garrido admitted to have become a supporter of [[FC Porto]], despite being himself a declared supporter of [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]] before ending his referee career. He was accused of collaborating with the former club, a claim which he denied.<ref name=\"publico\"/><ref name=\"expresso\"/><ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nOn 10 September 2014, he died after a long illness.<ref name=\"publico\" /><ref name=\"expresso\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Morreu o antigo \u00e1rbitro Ant\u00f3nio Garrido|language=Portuguese|trans-title=Former referee Ant\u00f3nio Garrido died|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-antonio-garrido-arbitro-arbitragem-morreu-antonio-garrido/5410252d0cf28f4fed8344d5.html|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Maisfutebol|date=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{WorldReferee.com}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|antonio-jose-da-silva-garrido/108034}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup Referees]] \n |before=[[1979 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1979]]<br />{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Erich Linemayr]] \n |after=[[1981 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1981]]<br />{{flagicon|HUN}} [[K\u00e1roly Palotai]] \n |years='''[[1980 European Cup Final|Final 1980]]<br />{{flagicon|POR}} Ant\u00f3nio Garrido'''}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{UEFA Champions League Final referees}}\n{{UEFA Euro 1980 referees}}\n{{1982 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrido, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Leiria District]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football referees]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1980 referees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Portuguese football referee}}\n{{Portuguese name|Silva|Garrido}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 da Silva Garrido\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1932|12|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Vieira de Leiria, [[Marinha Grande]], Portugal\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2014|9|10|1932|12|3|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Portuguese\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = [[Accountant]]\n| known_for   = [[Referee (association football)|Football referee]] <small>(1964\u20131982)</small>\n}}\n'''Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 da Silva Garrido''' <small>[[Order of Prince Henry|OIH]]</small> (3 December 1932 \u2013 10 September 2014) was a Portuguese [[association football|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in Vieira de Leiria, [[Marinha Grande]], Garrido was the first Portuguese referee to officiate a [[1980 European Cup Final|European Cup final]] in 1980. He refereed three matches in the [[FIFA World Cup]], two in the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]] and one in the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]] \u2013 the 3rd place play-off match. He also refereed one match in the [[UEFA Euro 1980]] and the first leg of [[1977 European Super Cup]].<ref name=\"publico\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publico.pt/desporto/noticia/antonio-garrido-o-homem-que-detestava-arbitros-mas-tornouse-um-deles-1669273 |title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido, o homem que detestava \u00e1rbitros mas que se tornou um deles |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido, the man who hated referees but that became one of them |author=Tiago Pimentel |date=10 September 2014 |website= |publisher=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]] |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 1983, Garrido received the title of Officer of the [[Order of Prince Henry]]. Although he was an [[accountant]] by profession, he continued involved in football after his forced retirement as a referee in 1982 due to age limit.<ref name=\"expresso\">{{cite web|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/morreu-o-arbitro-que-se-dizia-do-sporting-mas-colaborou-com-o-fc-porto=f888974|title=Morreu o \u00e1rbitro que se dizia do Sporting mas colaborou com o FC Porto|date=10 September 2014|website=|publisher=[[Expresso (Portuguese newspaper)|Expresso]]|language=Portuguese|trans-title=The referee who said being a Sporting fan but who collaborated with FC Porto|last1=Paulo|first1=Isabel|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref> He then had several positions, becoming member of the [[Portuguese Football Federation|FPF]]'s Refereeing Board (for 4 years), [[FIFA]] referee instructor, [[UEFA]] observer, and referees commissioner in World Cups (for 20 years).<ref name=\"publico\"/><ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido: \"Marquei penalties quase sem ter visto\" |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Ant\u00f3nio Garrido: \"I whistled penalties almost without seeing them\" |url=http://www.jornaldeleiria.pt/portal/index.php?id=7538 |accessdate=10 September 2014 |work=Jornal de Leiria |date=26 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910111809/http://www.jornaldeleiria.pt/portal/index.php?id=7538 |archivedate=10 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Garrido was heard as a witness in Portuguese corruption scandal [[Apito Dourado]] (Golden Whistle) for being tapped talking to Pinto de Sousa (Chairman of the FPF's Refereeing Board) and [[Valentim Loureiro]] (Chairman of the [[Portuguese League for Professional Football]]).<ref name=\"publico\"/><ref name=\"marca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2011/05/04/futbol/europa_league/1304504345.html|title=Directivos del Oporto cenaron con el \u00e1rbitro tras el partido contra el Villarreal|date=4 May 2011|website=[[Marca.com]]|language=Spanish|trans-title=FC Porto members dined with the referee after the match against Villarreal|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===1978 World Cup===\nGarrido officiated the match between the hosts [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Scott Murray and Paul Doyle|date=2 July 2010|title=The Joy of Six: World Cup Refereeing Controversies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/jul/02/joy-six-world-cup-refereeing-controversies|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== UEFA Euro 1980 ===\nGarrido also officiated the match between Italy and Belgium at [[UEFA Euro 1980]].\n\n==Personal life and death==\nIn 2012, Garrido admitted to have become a supporter of [[FC Porto]], despite being himself a declared supporter of [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]] before ending his referee career. He was accused of collaborating with the former club, a claim which he denied.<ref name=\"publico\"/><ref name=\"expresso\"/><ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nOn 10 September 2014, he died after a long illness.<ref name=\"publico\" /><ref name=\"expresso\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Morreu o antigo \u00e1rbitro Ant\u00f3nio Garrido|language=Portuguese|trans-title=Former referee Ant\u00f3nio Garrido died|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/liga-antonio-garrido-arbitro-arbitragem-morreu-antonio-garrido/5410252d0cf28f4fed8344d5.html|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Maisfutebol|date=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup Referees]] \n |before=[[1979 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1979]]<br />{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Erich Linemayr]] \n |after=[[1981 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1981]]<br />{{flagicon|HUN}} [[K\u00e1roly Palotai]] \n |years='''[[1980 European Cup Final|Final 1980]]<br />{{flagicon|POR}} Ant\u00f3nio Garrido'''}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{UEFA Champions League Final referees}}\n{{UEFA Euro 1980 referees}}\n{{1982 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrido, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Leiria District]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football referees]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1978 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1982 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1980 referees]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant%C3%B3nio_Garrido_(referee)"}
